Am I in somebody's lap?

262
00:10:16,166 --> 00:10:17,625
- [gasps]
You're awake?

263
00:10:17,708 --> 00:10:19,750
- A little weird for a cute girl
to be this hairy,

264
00:10:19,833 --> 00:10:21,291
but whatever.
Wait!

265
00:10:21,375 --> 00:10:22,625
This can't be right!

266
00:10:24,250 --> 00:10:25,250
[shouts]

267
00:10:25,333 --> 00:10:26,333
- We were just trying

268
00:10:26,416 --> 00:10:27,666
to make you happy
and comfortable

269
00:10:27,750 --> 00:10:28,791
until you woke up.

270
00:10:28,875 --> 00:10:30,541
There's no reason
to get freaked out.

271
00:10:30,625 --> 00:10:32,500
- First of all,
stop talking in that high voice.

272
00:10:32,583 --> 00:10:34,166
Nobody with half a brain
would confuse a cat

273
00:10:34,250 --> 00:10:35,291
for the main heroine.

274
00:10:35,375 --> 00:10:36,833
- Aww, just listen to you.

275
00:10:36,916 --> 00:10:39,750
Seeing you so happy made turning
myself bigger totally worth it.

276
00:10:39,833 --> 00:10:41,791
- I'm not happy at all!
[grunts]

277
00:10:41,875 --> 00:10:43,291
- [laughs]

278
00:10:43,375 --> 00:10:44,458
<i>[quirky music]</i>

279
00:10:44,541 --> 00:10:46,125
- I'm sorry about this.

280
00:10:46,208 --> 00:10:47,583
You stayed with me
the whole time

281
00:10:47,666 --> 00:10:49,041
I was unconscious.

282
00:10:49,125 --> 00:10:50,458
- Don't get the wrong idea.

283
00:10:50,541 --> 00:10:52,416
I only stuck around because
there are some things

284
00:10:52,500 --> 00:10:53,583
I wanna ask you.

285
00:10:53,666 --> 00:10:54,583
I took the time and trouble

286
00:10:54,666 --> 00:10:55,791
to heal your wounds for you.

287
00:10:55,875 --> 00:10:57,250
I also made Puck act
as your pillow

288
00:10:57,333 --> 00:10:59,791
until you finally woke up.
This was for my own benefit,

289
00:10:59,875 --> 00:11:02,291
but now that you're up,
I need you to repay me in kind.

290
00:11:02,375 --> 00:11:03,708
- Well, for such a normal favor,

291
00:11:03,791 --> 00:11:05,625
you're making it sound like
I really owe you big time.

292
00:11:05,708 --> 00:11:07,208
- That's not the way I see it.

293
00:11:07,291 --> 00:11:10,541
Now then, you have an idea
who stole my insignia, right?

294
00:11:10,625 --> 00:11:12,041
- What?
Hang on.

295
00:11:12,125 --> 00:11:13,916
Is your insignia one
of those badge things

296
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:15,208
that shows your social status?

297
00:11:15,291 --> 00:11:16,625
- A rather crude description,

298
00:11:16,708 --> 00:11:17,833
but that's it,
more or less.

299
00:11:17,916 --> 00:11:20,250
About this big
with a jewel in the center.

300
00:11:20,333 --> 00:11:23,166
- I'm sorry but no matter
how many times you ask,

301
00:11:23,250 --> 00:11:24,708
I still won't know.
- I see.

302
00:11:24,791 --> 00:11:26,250
I guess there's no helping that,

303
00:11:26,333 --> 00:11:27,583
but you've given me
the information

304
00:11:27,666 --> 00:11:28,875
that you know nothing,

305
00:11:28,958 --> 00:11:30,458
and that answer was in exchange
for healing you,

306
00:11:30,541 --> 00:11:32,916
so I'm still somewhat satisfied
with how things turned out.

307
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:33,916
- Okay.

308
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:35,166
- Well, I'm in quite a hurry,

309
00:11:35,250 --> 00:11:36,208
so I have to go.

310
00:11:36,291 --> 00:11:37,333
Your wounds should
be better now,

311
00:11:37,416 --> 00:11:38,750
but I highly suggest
that next time

312
00:11:38,833 --> 00:11:40,000
you don't do dangerous things

313
00:11:40,083 --> 00:11:41,625
like wander
into deserted alleys alone.

314
00:11:41,708 --> 00:11:42,833
[gasps]
I'm not concerned.

315
00:11:42,916 --> 00:11:43,833
I'm just warning you.

316
00:11:43,916 --> 00:11:44,958
If anything like that happens

317
00:11:45,041 --> 00:11:46,000
to you again,

318
00:11:46,083 --> 00:11:47,000
I already know that saving you

319
00:11:47,083 --> 00:11:47,958
won't be of any benefit to me,

320
00:11:48,041 --> 00:11:49,541
so don't expect any help.
Bye.

321
00:11:51,458 --> 00:11:54,125
- Sorry.
She's so insincere sometimes,

322
00:11:54,208 --> 00:11:56,250
but don't think badly of her,
okay?

323
00:12:00,916 --> 00:12:02,583
- Insincere, huh?

324
00:12:03,083 --> 00:12:04,708
I think this goes beyond that.

325
00:12:04,791 --> 00:12:07,583
She was in such a hurry
to find what was stolen from her

326
00:12:07,666 --> 00:12:09,166
yet she stopped to help me.

327
00:12:09,250 --> 00:12:11,833
She even came up with that
lame excuse for a favor

328
00:12:11,916 --> 00:12:13,125
so I wouldn't feel I owed her,

329
00:12:13,208 --> 00:12:15,041
even though I'm
a total stranger.

330
00:12:15,125 --> 00:12:16,708
Anyone who lives like that--

331
00:12:16,791 --> 00:12:18,833
[grunting]

332
00:12:18,916 --> 00:12:20,333
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

333
00:12:20,416 --> 00:12:22,875
Is just gonna end up wasting
their whole life!

334
00:12:24,208 --> 00:12:25,333
Hey, wait up!

335
00:12:25,416 --> 00:12:27,458
<i>♪ ♪</i>

336
00:12:27,541 --> 00:12:29,208
- Was there something else
you needed?

337
00:12:29,291 --> 00:12:30,250
Just so you know,

338
00:12:30,333 --> 00:12:31,541
I can only spend
a little more time

339
00:12:31,625 --> 00:12:32,625
with you, okay?

340
00:12:32,708 --> 00:12:34,083
- Figured you
were gonna shut me down.

341
00:12:34,166 --> 00:12:35,958
Anyway, you lost something
important, right?

342
00:12:36,041 --> 00:12:37,625
Well then,
let me help you find it.

343
00:12:37,708 --> 00:12:40,166
- You said you didn't
know anything about my insignia.

344
00:12:40,250 --> 00:12:41,625
- But I can remember her face!

345
00:12:41,708 --> 00:12:42,958
If I see her again,
I'll know!

346
00:12:43,833 --> 00:12:45,291
- [groans]

347
00:12:46,833 --> 00:12:48,250
You're so strange.

348
00:12:48,333 --> 00:12:49,625
Well, anyway,
I won't be able

349
00:12:49,708 --> 00:12:50,875
to offer you any reward.

350
00:12:50,958 --> 00:12:52,166
- Listen, I don't need one.

351
00:12:52,250 --> 00:12:53,791
I'm here because
I wanna thank you

352
00:12:53,875 --> 00:12:55,458
and to show how much
I appreciate your help.

353
00:12:55,541 --> 00:12:57,541
- I didn't do anything
deserving of that.

354
00:12:57,625 --> 00:13:00,541
I told you I've already
received amicable compensation

355
00:13:00,625 --> 00:13:01,833
for healing your wounds.

356
00:13:01,916 --> 00:13:03,166
- In that case,

357
00:13:03,250 --> 00:13:05,750
I guess I'm gonna help you
for my own sake, too.

358
00:13:05,833 --> 00:13:09,083
I should probably set
an objective, so, uh, right.

359
00:13:09,166 --> 00:13:11,250
One good deed per day.

360
00:13:11,333 --> 00:13:13,416
- U--uh...

361
00:13:13,958 --> 00:13:14,916
[groans]

362
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:16,416
- I don't sense any malice here,

363
00:13:16,500 --> 00:13:18,083
so I think you can
just accept his offer.

364
00:13:18,166 --> 00:13:19,250
After all,

365
00:13:19,333 --> 00:13:20,416
the more shields between you

366
00:13:20,500 --> 00:13:21,458
and the ruffians,
the better.

367
00:13:21,541 --> 00:13:22,583
- A shield?

368
00:13:22,666 --> 00:13:24,000
That's what you want me
around for?

369
00:13:24,083 --> 00:13:25,333
- I meant what I said, though.

370
00:13:25,416 --> 00:13:27,083
I can't do anything
to reward you.

371
00:13:27,166 --> 00:13:29,541
- No problem at all.
Just leave everything to me.

372
00:13:30,791 --> 00:13:33,708
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

373
00:13:33,791 --> 00:13:40,791
<i>♪ ♪</i>

374
00:13:46,375 --> 00:13:48,125
I know what I told you before,

375
00:13:48,208 --> 00:13:51,458
but isn't this town too huge
to find one little thing in?

376
00:13:51,541 --> 00:13:53,958
- This town is the capital
of Lugunica.

377
00:13:54,041 --> 00:13:55,916
How could you possibly
not know that?

378
00:13:56,000 --> 00:13:57,458
Uh...
- Hey, that's right.

379
00:13:57,541 --> 00:13:59,500
How rude of us.
We haven't asked his name yet.

380
00:13:59,583 --> 00:14:01,458
Shouldn't we all
introduce ourselves?

381
00:14:01,541 --> 00:14:02,666
- Oh, yeah.
Guess so.

382
00:14:02,750 --> 00:14:03,833
Might as well go ahead

383
00:14:03,916 --> 00:14:05,583
and get the ball rolling first,
then.

384
00:14:06,416 --> 00:14:08,000
My name is Subaru Natsuki.

385
00:14:08,083 --> 00:14:09,500
Not only am I totally clueless,

386
00:14:09,583 --> 00:14:12,291
I'm also broke beyond compare!
Nice to meet ya!

387
00:14:12,375 --> 00:14:13,958
- And that's how
you introduce yourself.

388
00:14:14,041 --> 00:14:15,666
You really do sound hopeless.

389
00:14:15,750 --> 00:14:17,458
And my name is Puck.

390
00:14:17,541 --> 00:14:19,916
It's nice to meet you!

391
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:21,208
[grunts]

392
00:14:21,291 --> 00:14:23,166
- It's very unusual
to see someone

393
00:14:23,250 --> 00:14:25,208
who can touch a spirit
so casually like that.

394
00:14:25,291 --> 00:14:26,500
Where are you from, exactly?

395
00:14:26,583 --> 00:14:28,416
- Well, if things follow
the usual pattern,

396
00:14:28,500 --> 00:14:30,333
it's a small island nation
to the east.

397
00:14:30,416 --> 00:14:33,000
- But Lugunica
is the eastern-most nation

398
00:14:33,083 --> 00:14:34,625
on our continental map.

399
00:14:34,708 --> 00:14:36,958
There are no more countries
in that direction.

400
00:14:37,041 --> 00:14:38,208
- No way.
Really?

401
00:14:38,291 --> 00:14:39,541
There's nothing east of here?

402
00:14:39,625 --> 00:14:41,291
- You have no idea
where you are,

403
00:14:41,375 --> 00:14:42,958
you have no money,
you can't read,

404
00:14:43,041 --> 00:14:46,000
and you seem to have
no one around who can help you.

405
00:14:46,083 --> 00:14:49,958
You might be in an even more
precarious position than I am.

406
00:14:50,041 --> 00:14:52,416
Uh, Subaru, right?
- Uh...

407
00:14:52,500 --> 00:14:53,958
[gasps]

408
00:14:54,041 --> 00:14:55,708
Yes, that's my name.

409
00:14:55,791 --> 00:14:57,875
- All that aside,
I gotta admit,

410
00:14:57,958 --> 00:14:59,458
you seem like you're
in pretty good shape.

411
00:14:59,541 --> 00:15:01,333
- I do try
to work out every day.

412
00:15:01,416 --> 00:15:03,458
- You see, when you're
the shut-in protector

413
00:15:03,541 --> 00:15:04,625
of your own house,

414
00:15:04,708 --> 00:15:06,291
you gotta stay fit
as much as possible.

415
00:15:06,375 --> 00:15:09,041
- I'm not sure if I understand
exactly what a shut-in is,

416
00:15:09,125 --> 00:15:10,208
but I assume it means

417
00:15:10,291 --> 00:15:12,083
you're from a reputable family,
right?

418
00:15:12,166 --> 00:15:14,375
- Hey, what are you--
- Your fingers, too.

419
00:15:14,458 --> 00:15:15,666
They're very pretty.

420
00:15:15,750 --> 00:15:17,166
They don't look like
the working hands

421
00:15:17,250 --> 00:15:18,375
of a peasant at all,

422
00:15:18,458 --> 00:15:19,625
and your muscles don't look

423
00:15:19,708 --> 00:15:21,750
like the kind you gain
from doing field work.

424
00:15:21,833 --> 00:15:23,166
- [gasps]

425
00:15:23,250 --> 00:15:24,791
U--um, yes.
So anyway,

426
00:15:24,875 --> 00:15:26,083
I know your cat's name now,

427
00:15:26,166 --> 00:15:28,000
but I still haven't heard
you say your name yet.

428
00:15:28,083 --> 00:15:30,041
- Oh, my name?
- [chuckles nervously]

429
00:15:30,125 --> 00:15:33,041
[wind blows]

430
00:15:33,125 --> 00:15:34,291
- It's...

431
00:15:38,083 --> 00:15:39,250
It's Satella.

432
00:15:39,333 --> 00:15:41,333
[both gasping]
No family name.

433
00:15:41,416 --> 00:15:43,708
So that's the way
you may address me, all right?

434
00:15:44,416 --> 00:15:45,666
- I see.

435
00:15:45,750 --> 00:15:47,208
Satella it is.

436
00:15:48,208 --> 00:15:49,583
That's a nice name.

437
00:15:50,458 --> 00:15:51,500
- [gasps]

438
00:15:51,958 --> 00:15:53,750
- [sighs]

439
00:15:53,833 --> 00:15:56,125
You have got terrible taste.

440
00:15:57,000 --> 00:15:57,916
- Right.

441
00:15:58,000 --> 00:15:59,791
Time to get back
to asking around!

442
00:16:02,375 --> 00:16:05,250
- Subaru,
that child over there,

443
00:16:05,333 --> 00:16:06,750
do you get the feeling
she's lost?

444
00:16:06,833 --> 00:16:07,750
- Uh?

445
00:16:07,833 --> 00:16:10,833
- [whimpering]

446
00:16:11,291 --> 00:16:13,375
- Maybe, but what about
our questioning?

447
00:16:13,458 --> 00:16:15,500
- That's also important,
but if she's lost,

448
00:16:15,583 --> 00:16:16,791
we have to do something.

449
00:16:17,375 --> 00:16:19,125
- [whimpering]

450
00:16:19,208 --> 00:16:21,958
- I'm in no place to talk
after you saved me,

451
00:16:22,041 --> 00:16:24,750
but do you fully comprehend
the position we're in?

452
00:16:24,833 --> 00:16:26,375
- I do,

453
00:16:26,458 --> 00:16:28,458
but there's a little girl
who's crying.

454
00:16:28,541 --> 00:16:30,166
You can see that, right?

455
00:16:30,250 --> 00:16:31,166
- [grunts]

456
00:16:31,250 --> 00:16:32,583
- If you don't wanna do this

457
00:16:32,666 --> 00:16:33,750
with me,
that's fine.

458
00:16:33,833 --> 00:16:35,708
Thanks for your assistance,
Subaru.

459
00:16:35,791 --> 00:16:38,208
I'm sure I can handle things
on my own from here on out,

460
00:16:38,291 --> 00:16:40,833
but first I'm gonna help
that little girl.

461
00:16:41,208 --> 00:16:43,625
- [whimpers]

462
00:16:43,708 --> 00:16:45,500
[gasps]

463
00:16:45,583 --> 00:16:46,666
- Hey there.

464
00:16:46,750 --> 00:16:48,375
It looks like something's
the matter.

465
00:16:48,458 --> 00:16:49,958
Maybe I can help you.

466
00:16:50,041 --> 00:16:52,916
Did you come here on your own
or with your mommy and daddy?

467
00:16:53,958 --> 00:16:57,166
- [whimpers]

468
00:16:57,250 --> 00:16:58,416
- Oh, I'm sorry!

469
00:16:58,500 --> 00:16:59,750
I didn't mean to make you cry.

470
00:16:59,833 --> 00:17:01,833
I'm just here to help,
not to do anything bad.

471
00:17:01,916 --> 00:17:03,041
I promise.

472
00:17:03,125 --> 00:17:05,041
- What you see before you
is a rarity around here;

473
00:17:05,125 --> 00:17:07,541
A jagged-edged 10 yen coin.
- [gasps]

474
00:17:07,625 --> 00:17:09,500
- Observe closely
as I take this coin

475
00:17:09,583 --> 00:17:11,166
and clutch it tightly
in my hand.

476
00:17:11,250 --> 00:17:13,083
Tight, tight, tight,
like that.

477
00:17:13,166 --> 00:17:15,750
Now, where'd it go?
- [gasps]

478
00:17:15,833 --> 00:17:16,833
Huh?

479
00:17:17,583 --> 00:17:18,666
- [chuckles]

480
00:17:18,750 --> 00:17:19,958
<i>[quirky music]</i>

481
00:17:20,041 --> 00:17:21,416
Well, take a look at this!

482
00:17:21,500 --> 00:17:24,125
I figured out where
the coin was hiding.

483
00:17:24,208 --> 00:17:26,125
- [gasps]

484
00:17:26,708 --> 00:17:27,791
- Here you go.
It's yours.

485
00:17:27,875 --> 00:17:29,125
Like I said,
it's rare,

486
00:17:29,208 --> 00:17:30,375
so take good care of it.

487
00:17:30,458 --> 00:17:31,833
- [exhales]

488
00:17:31,916 --> 00:17:33,000
[giggles]

489
00:17:33,083 --> 00:17:34,375
Thank you, sir!

490
00:17:34,958 --> 00:17:36,000
- I see.

491
00:17:36,083 --> 00:17:37,875
You got separated
from your mom, huh?

492
00:17:37,958 --> 00:17:39,750
Yeah, that can be kinda scary.

493
00:17:39,833 --> 00:17:42,000
Well, don't worry.
We'll help you.

494
00:17:42,083 --> 00:17:43,375
Me and this
young lady right here,

495
00:17:43,458 --> 00:17:45,166
we'll find them
in no time for you.

496
00:17:46,458 --> 00:17:48,000
Wow, look at us.

497
00:17:48,083 --> 00:17:50,125
<i>People who don't know us</i>
<i>probably think they're looking</i>

498
00:17:50,208 --> 00:17:52,166
<i>at a young married couple</i>
<i>and their kid, huh?</i>

499
00:17:52,250 --> 00:17:54,500
<i>Is that embarrassing or what?</i>
<i>- At best,</i>

500
00:17:54,583 --> 00:17:56,291
<i>I can't really see you</i>
<i>as anything more</i>

501
00:17:56,375 --> 00:17:57,541
<i>than her older brother.</i>

502
00:17:57,625 --> 00:17:59,458
- What makes you think
I'm so young, huh?

503
00:17:59,541 --> 00:18:01,625
- [gasps]
Mommy!

504
00:18:01,708 --> 00:18:03,833
[both gasping]

505
00:18:03,916 --> 00:18:05,708
Mommy!
- [laughing]

506
00:18:05,791 --> 00:18:08,000
- It looks like
she finally found her.

507
00:18:08,083 --> 00:18:10,041
- Yeah.
I'm so relieved.

508
00:18:10,750 --> 00:18:13,166
- Okay, so in my opinion,

509
00:18:13,250 --> 00:18:15,083
that whole string of events
with the little girl

510
00:18:15,166 --> 00:18:16,375
was nothing but a side quest,

511
00:18:16,458 --> 00:18:17,583
but what benefit
will you insist

512
00:18:17,666 --> 00:18:18,833
that you got out of it?
Go on.

513
00:18:18,916 --> 00:18:20,250
Tell me.
- That's easy.

514
00:18:20,333 --> 00:18:22,500
Now we can continue our search
with our minds at ease

515
00:18:22,583 --> 00:18:24,083
knowing we did the right thing.

516
00:18:24,166 --> 00:18:27,000
Anyway, why'd you end up
helping me with that?

517
00:18:27,083 --> 00:18:28,583
Thought you said
you were against the idea.

518
00:18:28,666 --> 00:18:31,083
- Could say I just wanted
to show off my magic trick,

519
00:18:31,166 --> 00:18:32,083
but that'd be a lie.

520
00:18:32,166 --> 00:18:33,625
Like I told you before,

521
00:18:33,708 --> 00:18:36,375
finding your insignia will be
my one good deed for the day.

522
00:18:36,458 --> 00:18:37,541
- I know that was the plan,

523
00:18:37,625 --> 00:18:38,916
but since you helped
the little girl,

524
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:40,458
isn't your one good deed over?

525
00:18:40,541 --> 00:18:43,000
- You are being super nit-picky!

526
00:18:43,083 --> 00:18:44,708
It doesn't hurt to do more
than one nice thing

527
00:18:44,791 --> 00:18:45,791
in a day,
does it?

528
00:18:45,875 --> 00:18:47,458
I just got tomorrow's out
of the way.

529
00:18:47,541 --> 00:18:49,208
My plan is to get a week's worth
of good deeds

530
00:18:49,291 --> 00:18:50,666
taken care of early.

531
00:18:51,416 --> 00:18:52,458
- If I were to guess,

532
00:18:52,541 --> 00:18:53,458
you're the type that basically

533
00:18:53,541 --> 00:18:54,750
wastes their whole life, right?

534
00:18:54,833 --> 00:18:56,416
- Seriously?
You're the last person

535
00:18:56,500 --> 00:18:58,041
who should be saying that
to anyone.

536
00:18:58,125 --> 00:18:59,958
- I admit you're not
a bad boy, though.

537
00:19:00,041 --> 00:19:02,041
- Why do you act like
I'm so much younger than you?

538
00:19:02,125 --> 00:19:03,625
Honestly, I'm guessing
there aren't that

539
00:19:03,708 --> 00:19:04,791
many differences between us.

540
00:19:04,875 --> 00:19:06,083
- Well, you may think that,

541
00:19:06,166 --> 00:19:08,291
but all of your guesses
would be wrong

542
00:19:08,375 --> 00:19:10,750
because I'm actually half elf.

543
00:19:10,833 --> 00:19:12,875
- [gasps]

544
00:19:12,958 --> 00:19:15,750
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

545
00:19:15,833 --> 00:19:17,791
Ah, no wonder.

546
00:19:17,875 --> 00:19:19,375
It makes sense now.

547
00:19:19,458 --> 00:19:21,958
From the moment I saw you,
I thought you were cute.

548
00:19:22,041 --> 00:19:23,791
Elves are always beautiful,
aren't they?

549
00:19:23,875 --> 00:19:24,958
- [gasps]

550
00:19:25,041 --> 00:19:25,916
- [grunts]

551
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:27,083
What is it?

552
00:19:27,166 --> 00:19:28,666
- Didn't you hear
what I just said?

553
00:19:28,750 --> 00:19:31,000
Listen, I'm trying to tell you
that I'm a half elf.

554
00:19:31,083 --> 00:19:32,375
- Yeah, I heard you.

555
00:19:33,375 --> 00:19:35,166
- [groans]

556
00:19:35,250 --> 00:19:36,500
[grunts]

557
00:19:37,541 --> 00:19:38,708
- [gasps]

558
00:19:38,791 --> 00:19:42,083
- [shouts]

559
00:19:42,166 --> 00:19:44,000
- What the heck did you
do that for?

560
00:19:44,083 --> 00:19:45,458
- I just had to do something

561
00:19:45,541 --> 00:19:47,333
about this unbearable tingle
I'm feeling.

562
00:19:47,416 --> 00:19:49,333
- That's the weirdest reason
for punching somebody

563
00:19:49,416 --> 00:19:51,041
I've ever heard,
though I'll forgive you,

564
00:19:51,125 --> 00:19:52,166
since it was squishy.

565
00:19:52,250 --> 00:19:53,250
- I didn't hit you in the face

566
00:19:53,333 --> 00:19:54,375
out of anger or anything!

567
00:19:54,458 --> 00:19:56,083
In fact,
it was quite the opposite!

568
00:19:56,166 --> 00:19:58,916
- Subaru, you are such
a dunderhead.

569
00:19:59,000 --> 00:20:01,583
- Yeah, so who says "dunderhead"
in this day and age?

570
00:20:01,666 --> 00:20:03,750
And why are you insulting me
in the first place?

571
00:20:03,833 --> 00:20:05,291
- [grunts]
Whatever.

572
00:20:05,375 --> 00:20:06,416
More importantly,

573
00:20:06,500 --> 00:20:08,000
we have to get back
to the search,

574
00:20:08,083 --> 00:20:09,333
so let's go.

575
00:20:09,833 --> 00:20:11,083
- Hey, wait a minute.

576
00:20:11,166 --> 00:20:12,791
Just running around
without a plan

577
00:20:12,875 --> 00:20:14,041
is never a good idea.

578
00:20:14,125 --> 00:20:15,750
There's a basic rule
of searches.

579
00:20:15,833 --> 00:20:17,125
- What are you talking about?

580
00:20:17,208 --> 00:20:19,458
- Yeah, like revisiting
the scene of the crime.

581
00:20:19,541 --> 00:20:21,375
Where exactly
was your insignia stolen?

582
00:20:21,458 --> 00:20:23,541
And then she told me
it was right around here,

583
00:20:23,625 --> 00:20:25,708
so after I insisted that
she leave everything to me,

584
00:20:25,791 --> 00:20:27,333
I valiantly came back
to this fruit stand

585
00:20:27,416 --> 00:20:28,541
to look for some clues.

586
00:20:28,625 --> 00:20:29,833
- I thought I had a customer,

587
00:20:29,916 --> 00:20:32,000
but you're that same broke kid
from earlier.

588
00:20:32,083 --> 00:20:34,333
- You really wanna take
that attitude?

589
00:20:34,416 --> 00:20:36,541
Haven't you noticed I'm not
who I was before?

590
00:20:36,625 --> 00:20:38,041
- Huh?

591
00:20:38,125 --> 00:20:39,875
- Just look who
I brought with me.

592
00:20:39,958 --> 00:20:43,125
I'd bet it's someone who
just might become a regular.

593
00:20:43,208 --> 00:20:44,708
- Uh, Subaru,

594
00:20:44,791 --> 00:20:47,291
I'm not exactly sure
what you expected of me,

595
00:20:47,375 --> 00:20:49,708
but I actually don't
have any money, either.

596
00:20:49,791 --> 00:20:51,625
- Huh?
S--seriously?

597
00:20:51,708 --> 00:20:53,416
- So what did you
wanna ask me about

598
00:20:53,500 --> 00:20:55,166
now that I'm stuck here
with not one

599
00:20:55,250 --> 00:20:57,458
but two broke customers, boy?

600
00:20:57,541 --> 00:20:59,708
- Well, we're actually looking
for someone,

601
00:20:59,791 --> 00:21:01,750
and we were hoping we could
ask you a few questions,

602
00:21:01,833 --> 00:21:02,791
if you wouldn't mind.

603
00:21:02,875 --> 00:21:04,208
- That was a sarcastic way
of saying

604
00:21:04,291 --> 00:21:05,916
I don't have time
for broke losers.

605
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:07,375
Now get out of here!
Scram!

606
00:21:07,458 --> 00:21:09,250
- Hey, mister!
[all grunting]

607
00:21:09,333 --> 00:21:11,291
- Thanks for your help earlier.

608
00:21:11,375 --> 00:21:13,083
- What brings you back this way?

609
00:21:13,166 --> 00:21:14,541
- It's my husband's shop,

610
00:21:14,625 --> 00:21:16,250
so we just wanted
to stop by.

611
00:21:16,333 --> 00:21:18,375
- [groans]
- Your husband?

612
00:21:19,625 --> 00:21:20,708
Uh...

613
00:21:20,791 --> 00:21:22,166
- [giggles]
- Huh?

614
00:21:22,250 --> 00:21:25,125
- [giggles]
- Hey, there's my girl.

615
00:21:25,208 --> 00:21:26,583
Now, wait a second.

616
00:21:26,666 --> 00:21:29,208
How exactly do you know
these two good-for-nothings?

617
00:21:29,291 --> 00:21:31,208
- She got lost
and these two found her

618
00:21:31,291 --> 00:21:32,791
and then helped
bring her back to me.

619
00:21:32,875 --> 00:21:34,750
- [snarls]
- [chuckles]

620
00:21:35,166 --> 00:21:37,083
- Thanks again, lady.
Here.

621
00:21:37,166 --> 00:21:38,500
- [gasps]

622
00:21:39,458 --> 00:21:41,291
- She was hoping we'd find you.

623
00:21:41,375 --> 00:21:43,666
Please accept that token
as her way of showing gratitude

624
00:21:43,750 --> 00:21:45,000
for what you've done.

625
00:21:46,916 --> 00:21:48,875
- Thank you very much.

626
00:21:48,958 --> 00:21:51,833
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

627
00:21:51,916 --> 00:21:52,833
[chuckles]

628
00:21:52,916 --> 00:21:54,541
- [giggles]

629
00:21:54,625 --> 00:21:56,833
- [clears throat]
[both gasps]

630
00:21:56,916 --> 00:21:58,708
Sorry about all that before.

631
00:21:58,791 --> 00:21:59,958
You helped my daughter.

632
00:22:00,041 --> 00:22:01,500
I wanna show my appreciation,

633
00:22:01,583 --> 00:22:03,166
so ask me anything.

634
00:22:03,250 --> 00:22:04,500
[both chuckling]

635
00:22:04,583 --> 00:22:05,916
[both gasp]

636
00:22:06,000 --> 00:22:07,125
- There, you see?

637
00:22:07,208 --> 00:22:08,958
A little bit of extra effort
on our part

638
00:22:09,041 --> 00:22:10,791
came back around
and worked in our favor.

639
00:22:14,666 --> 00:22:17,583
<i>[uneasy music]</i>

640
00:22:17,666 --> 00:22:24,708
<i>♪ ♪</i>

641
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:31,750
- The air,
the atmosphere,

642
00:22:31,833 --> 00:22:33,083
and most likely the attitudes

643
00:22:33,166 --> 00:22:35,000
of the people living here
are awful.

644
00:22:35,083 --> 00:22:36,916
Are you sure
she's really out here?

645
00:22:37,625 --> 00:22:39,666
- You're saying she's
a nimble little blonde, right?

646
00:22:39,750 --> 00:22:40,916
'Cause it might be
that Felt girl

647
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:42,625
I see around from time to time.

648
00:22:42,708 --> 00:22:45,416
She's well-known in the slums.
Dunno where she lives, though.

649
00:22:45,500 --> 00:22:47,333
That's about all I can tell you.

650
00:22:47,708 --> 00:22:50,000
- Maybe someone will tell us
if we ask.

651
00:22:50,083 --> 00:22:51,583
- No one would sell out
their own,

652
00:22:51,666 --> 00:22:53,333
especially to a couple
of strangers,

653
00:22:53,416 --> 00:22:54,958
so asking would be useless.

654
00:22:55,041 --> 00:22:57,416
- Maybe we should just
come back later.

655
00:22:57,500 --> 00:22:59,083
- Whatever it is you wanna do,

656
00:22:59,166 --> 00:23:01,000
I suggest that
you decide quickly,

657
00:23:01,083 --> 00:23:03,166
'cause I've just about run out
of time here.

658
00:23:03,250 --> 00:23:04,916
- Out of time?
What do you mean?

659
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:06,958
- I'm able to take on
this cute appearance

660
00:23:07,041 --> 00:23:08,458
but I'm a spirit.

661
00:23:08,541 --> 00:23:11,791
It takes a lot of mana for me
to appear in physical form.

662
00:23:12,291 --> 00:23:13,708
So when the day becomes night,

663
00:23:13,791 --> 00:23:15,875
I return to the crystal
I was summoned from

664
00:23:15,958 --> 00:23:17,666
and prepare for the sun
to emerge.

665
00:23:17,750 --> 00:23:19,166
[sighs]
On average,

666
00:23:19,250 --> 00:23:21,833
my ideal time to stay out
is roughly 9:00 to 5:00.

667
00:23:21,916 --> 00:23:23,041
- 9:00 to 5:00?

668
00:23:23,125 --> 00:23:24,541
Sounds like you work
in an office.

669
00:23:24,625 --> 00:23:27,250
Employment terms for spirits
are pretty severe.

670
00:23:27,333 --> 00:23:28,958
- We'll be fine without Puck.

671
00:23:29,041 --> 00:23:30,875
We need to keep moving forward
on this.

672
00:23:30,958 --> 00:23:35,500
- Sorry, but I'm at my limit.
Good luck, you two.

673
00:23:35,583 --> 00:23:37,625
- It's almost like he's dying
when he disappears.

674
00:23:37,708 --> 00:23:40,250
- Sorry to have worked you
so hard today, Puck.

675
00:23:40,333 --> 00:23:41,458
We'll handle things from here,

676
00:23:41,541 --> 00:23:43,500
so settle in
and get some rest.

677
00:23:43,583 --> 00:23:45,666
- [exhales]

678
00:23:45,750 --> 00:23:47,875
Don't do anything reckless,
all right?

679
00:23:47,958 --> 00:23:49,250
If it comes down to it,

680
00:23:49,333 --> 00:23:51,291
you can always use the od
to summon me again.

681
00:23:51,375 --> 00:23:52,583
- [grunts]

682
00:23:52,666 --> 00:23:54,250
- I'm leaving things
in your hands, Subaru.

683
00:23:54,333 --> 00:23:55,666
Good luck.

684
00:23:57,583 --> 00:23:59,750
- [gasps]

685
00:23:59,833 --> 00:24:00,916
[whooshing]

686
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:02,416
[gasps]

687
00:24:04,833 --> 00:24:05,875
Hey, wow.

688
00:24:05,958 --> 00:24:06,916
I don't think I've been in one
of these

689
00:24:07,000 --> 00:24:08,291
alone-with-a-girl situations

690
00:24:08,375 --> 00:24:09,666
since I was in grade school.

691
00:24:09,750 --> 00:24:12,000
- Don't get any pervy ideas,
Subaru.

692
00:24:12,083 --> 00:24:13,875
I can use magic, you know.

693
00:24:13,958 --> 00:24:15,208
- I won't, okay?

694
00:24:15,291 --> 00:24:18,916
The more important issue at hand
is how we find Felt now.

695
00:24:19,000 --> 00:24:21,375
- I'll contact
the lesser spirits.

696
00:24:21,458 --> 00:24:23,625
- Lesser spirits?
- Precisely.

697
00:24:23,708 --> 00:24:25,291
They're beings
that haven't quite

698
00:24:25,375 --> 00:24:27,041
become full fledged spirits yet.

699
00:24:27,125 --> 00:24:28,875
They grow little by little
over time,

700
00:24:28,958 --> 00:24:30,000
and when they gain
enough strength

701
00:24:30,083 --> 00:24:31,208
and self awareness,

702
00:24:31,291 --> 00:24:33,166
they become full spirits
just like Puck.

703
00:24:34,666 --> 00:24:37,291
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

704
00:24:37,375 --> 00:24:38,416
- Huh?

705
00:24:38,500 --> 00:24:44,208
<i>♪ ♪</i>

706
00:24:44,291 --> 00:24:45,458
Uh...

707
00:24:45,541 --> 00:24:52,583
<i>♪ ♪</i>

708
00:24:55,541 --> 00:24:57,041
Oh.

709
00:24:57,125 --> 00:25:04,208
<i>♪ ♪</i>

710
00:25:17,083 --> 00:25:20,125
[crickets chirping]

711
00:25:20,208 --> 00:25:22,750
- It's getting more desolate
and quiet.

712
00:25:22,833 --> 00:25:25,500
- Hard to believe that
she actually lives out here.

713
00:25:25,583 --> 00:25:28,458
- I know, but the lesser spirits
specifically said

714
00:25:28,541 --> 00:25:30,291
they saw someone who looked
like Felt headed

715
00:25:30,375 --> 00:25:31,583
in this direction.

716
00:25:35,166 --> 00:25:36,833
- Excuse me, man.

717
00:25:36,916 --> 00:25:39,458
Know if a girl named Felt
lives somewhere up this way?

718
00:25:39,541 --> 00:25:41,583
- Huh?
You're looking for Felt?

719
00:25:41,666 --> 00:25:42,583
- Mm-hmm.

720
00:25:42,666 --> 00:25:43,541
- There's nothing that way

721
00:25:43,625 --> 00:25:45,416
except Old Man Rom's loot house.

722
00:25:45,500 --> 00:25:46,416
[chuckles]

723
00:25:46,500 --> 00:25:47,458
I guess she must have stolen

724
00:25:47,541 --> 00:25:48,583
something pretty important

725
00:25:48,666 --> 00:25:49,958
for you two to come out here.

726
00:25:50,041 --> 00:25:51,541
Well, I wish you luck
on bargaining

727
00:25:51,625 --> 00:25:53,791
to try to get it back.
Live strong, okay?

728
00:25:54,708 --> 00:25:55,875
[both gasping]

729
00:25:55,958 --> 00:25:59,000
[distant wolves howling]

730
00:26:00,916 --> 00:26:02,666
- What was he talking about?

731
00:26:02,750 --> 00:26:04,291
Why do I have to pay money
to get back

732
00:26:04,375 --> 00:26:06,041
something stolen from me?

733
00:26:06,125 --> 00:26:07,541
- Don't worry about a thing.

734
00:26:07,625 --> 00:26:09,125
Just leave everything to me.

735
00:26:09,208 --> 00:26:11,375
I can handle the negotiations.

736
00:26:12,458 --> 00:26:13,583
- All right, then.

737
00:26:13,666 --> 00:26:15,500
I'll just leave everything
in your hands.

738
00:26:15,583 --> 00:26:17,291
- You agreed
to that pretty easily.

739
00:26:17,375 --> 00:26:19,083
I figured you'd
say something like,

740
00:26:19,166 --> 00:26:21,375
"You want me to leave this
to a useless boy like you?

741
00:26:21,458 --> 00:26:24,208
"That's such a ridiculous idea,
it actually hurts my stomach."

742
00:26:24,291 --> 00:26:25,958
And although that would stomp
all over my feelings,

743
00:26:26,041 --> 00:26:27,500
I'd still decide
to keep helping you anyway.

744
00:26:27,583 --> 00:26:29,750
- I'd never say something
that mean to anyone.

745
00:26:29,833 --> 00:26:31,333
Of course,
to tell you the truth,

746
00:26:31,416 --> 00:26:33,125
I'd be lying if I said
you haven't been holding

747
00:26:33,208 --> 00:26:34,250
me back a little bit.

748
00:26:34,333 --> 00:26:35,625
- Oh, great!
That's good to know!

749
00:26:35,708 --> 00:26:38,875
- But again,
I'm leaving this in your hands.

750
00:26:38,958 --> 00:26:40,125
- [gasps]

751
00:26:40,625 --> 00:26:41,916
- If it actually goes well,

752
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:43,291
I'll consider it a bonus.

753
00:26:43,375 --> 00:26:45,125
- Now, you know,
if you said something more like,

754
00:26:45,208 --> 00:26:46,583
"Work hard for me, okay?"

755
00:26:46,666 --> 00:26:48,666
I'd probably feel
a whole lot more motivated.

756
00:26:48,750 --> 00:26:51,333
- Sorry, I can't force myself
to say something like that.

757
00:26:51,833 --> 00:26:54,708
However, please do your best.

758
00:26:55,416 --> 00:26:56,458
- [exhales]

759
00:26:56,541 --> 00:26:58,166
[chuckles]
Yeah, you got it.

760
00:26:58,250 --> 00:26:59,708
I'll go in first.

761
00:26:59,791 --> 00:27:01,250
You stay outside
and keep watch.

762
00:27:01,333 --> 00:27:02,375
I won't be back too late,

763
00:27:02,458 --> 00:27:03,416
but you can have dinner
without me

764
00:27:03,500 --> 00:27:04,500
if you get too hungry.

765
00:27:04,583 --> 00:27:06,000
- Don't say dumb things
like that.

766
00:27:06,083 --> 00:27:07,208
- Okay, let's see here.
- And be careful.

767
00:27:07,291 --> 00:27:08,750
- Sure, sure.

768
00:27:08,833 --> 00:27:11,666
Now, don't come in until
I say it's all right, Satella.

769
00:27:14,541 --> 00:27:15,791
What's the matter?
- [gasps]

770
00:27:15,875 --> 00:27:17,708
[grunts]
Nothing, never mind.

771
00:27:17,791 --> 00:27:20,208
If you can manage
to get my insignia back,

772
00:27:20,291 --> 00:27:21,541
then I'll apologize.

773
00:27:24,833 --> 00:27:26,083
- Anybody here?

774
00:27:26,166 --> 00:27:27,291
Nope.

